f:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","FTM","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"FTM/USDT on MEXC presents compelling funding arbitrage opportunities due to Fantom's volatility and MEXC's aggressive listing strategy attracting speculative traders. The combination of zero maker fees and substantial leverage options creates favorable conditions for funding rate harvesting strategies, especially during periods of high market sentiment around L1 blockchain narratives."}]]}]
10:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"FTM/USDT funding rates on MEXC have historically shown significant volatility, often ranging from -0.5% to +1.2% during major market movements. The pair exhibits particularly high positive funding rates during Fantom ecosystem developments or broader L1 rallies, as retail traders heavily favor long positions. During bear markets or ecosystem setbacks, funding rates frequently turn negative as shorts dominate, creating opportunities for contrarian funding strategies. MEXC's early listing advantage means FTM funding patterns often lead other exchanges during initial price discovery phases."}]]}]
11:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"The zero maker fee structure on MEXC creates unique funding arbitrage setups for FTM/USDT, allowing traders to delta-hedge positions without incurring entry costs. Cross-exchange funding arbitrage opportunities emerge frequently, as MEXC's funding rates often diverge from larger exchanges like Binance or OKX due to different trader demographics. High leverage availability (up to 125x) enables capital-efficient funding strategies, though traders must carefully manage liquidation risks. The 8-hour funding cycle provides multiple daily opportunities to capture rate differentials compared to exchanges with different funding schedules."}]]}]
12:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's thinner order books for FTM/USDT can create significant slippage during large position adjustments, particularly problematic for sizeable funding arbitrage operations. The exchange's questionable volume reporting raises concerns about actual liquidity depth, potentially leading to unexpected execution issues during volatile periods. Limited regulatory compliance compared to tier-1 exchanges introduces counterparty risk, especially for larger funding arbitrage positions that require extended holding periods. Traders should also consider MEXC's tendency to delist underperforming tokens, which could impact long-term funding strategies on FTM/USDT."}]]}]
13:["$","$L15",null,{"items":[{"question":"What are the typical FTM/USDT funding rates on MEXC?","answer":"FTM/USDT funding rates on MEXC typically range from -0.3% to +0.8% during normal market conditions, with extreme rates reaching ±1.5% during major Fantom developments or broader market volatility. The rates are generally higher than established coins due to increased speculative activity."},{"question":"How does MEXC's zero maker fee affect FTM funding arbitrage?","answer":"Zero maker fees on MEXC eliminate entry costs for funding arbitrage strategies, allowing traders to establish hedge positions without trading costs. This creates a significant advantage over exchanges charging maker fees, especially for high-frequency funding collection strategies on FTM/USDT."},{"question":"What liquidity risks exist for FTM/USDT funding arbitrage on MEXC?","answer":"MEXC's FTM/USDT order book is typically thinner than tier-1 exchanges, creating slippage risks during position adjustments. Large funding arbitrage positions may face execution challenges, particularly during volatile periods when immediate hedging adjustments are required."},{"question":"How reliable is MEXC for long-term FTM funding strategies?","answer":"While MEXC offers competitive funding mechanics for FTM, the exchange's limited regulatory compliance and history of token delistings create risks for extended funding strategies. Traders should consider these factors when planning long-term funding arbitrage positions on FTM/USDT."}]}]
